# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The book was reviewed in contemporary periodicals including the *London Medical Gazette*, *The Athenaeum*, and *The Veterinary Record*.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] It was later noted by writers including Henry S.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Ralph Fletcher (1780—1851) was a surgeon based in Gloucester.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He studied at St Bartholomew's Hospital in London and received an M.D. from the University of Edinburgh Medical School.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He held appointments at the Gloucester Infirmary, Dispensary, and Lunatic Asylum.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He published medical papers on the relation between mental and physical health.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher was twice elected Mayor of Gloucester and served as president of the local branch of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He lived on Barton Street, near the city's animal pound, and his observations of the animals kept there were said to have inspired *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals*.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In a brief "Preliminary Note", Fletcher writes about the suffering of animals, especially those dependent on humans.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He rejects the view that animals are insensible to pain or that their suffering is divinely ordained, and argues for compassion on moral and theological grounds.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In "Importance of the Subject", Fletcher draws on his experience as president of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes that public acts of cruelty form only a small part of a wider problem, and that abuse often takes place in private spaces such as stables, slaughterhouses, and homes.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He argues that existing legislation was inadequate, because small fines and judicial discretion to reduce sentences did not deter offenders.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The main part of the book consists of notes on individual animals and practices.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher describes donkeys as animals commonly subjected to overwork and neglect.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He condemns blood sports such as shooting tied cocks and badger-baiting.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] His discussion of cats and dogs contrasts their treatment: he writes that cats were often tormented or killed for amusement, while dogs suffered from starvation, beatings, cart-work, and fighting.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher criticises methods used in the rearing and slaughter of calves and lambs, including starvation and repeated bleeding to produce white veal.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes about overwork, neglect, and abandonment, and argues that owners as well as drivers should be held legally responsible.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher ends by calling for tougher penalties for cruelty, official oversight of slaughterhouses and stables, wider public instruction in humane treatment, and hospitals for sick and injured animals.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] A review in the *London Medical Gazette* described the book as the work of a hospital surgeon acquainted with suffering.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The reviewer agreed with Fletcher's criticism of animal experimentation, but called his proposal for hospitals for animals a "somewhat Utopian scheme" said to have some precedent in the East.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Salt in the "Bibliography of Animal Rights" section of his 1892 work *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress*, where he referred to it as a treatise on animal cruelty.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In his 1989 reference work *Keyguide to Information Sources in Animal Rights*, Charles R.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Magel described *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals* as an early account of animal abuse in the Gloucester area and noted its proposal for hospitals for animals modelled on human institutions.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Wall was the son of Abiathar Brown Wall, a physician of Bayswater.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He was educated at St Bartholomew's Hospital and studied surgery at London Hospital.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He also studied medicine at Edinburgh University.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] After he qualified he became an assistant to his father and took up an appointment in India where he resided for several years.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Upon returning he settled at Thornton Avenue, Streatham Hill where he established his practice for 28 years.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Wall was an advocate of animal welfare and a staunch opponent of vivisection.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He argued that animals especially vertebrates have mental faculties identical with those of man such as intelligence, memory and sympathy and as they are capable of intense suffering, we have no right to inflict such suffering.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Wall was a member of the International Society for the Suppression of Vivisection.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] In 1881, Wall co-authored *Vivisection Scientifically and Ethically Considered in Prize Essays*, a collection of prize-winning essays exploring the ethics of vivisection.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] A prize of two hundred guineas was offered by an anonymous benefactor for the best essay against vivisection and seven judges were appointed to weigh the merits of the competitors.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] A review noted that the book presented "the case of the anti-vivisectionists clearly and strongly".
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He was a speaker on anti-vivisection and attended meetings throughout the United Kingdom and at congresses in Paris and Zurich.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] His 1892 paper at the Nottingham anti-vivisection congress was reprinted and translated.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He served on the committee of the London Anti-Vivisection Society and became its honorary treasurer and a trustee.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He was a co-founder of the National Anti-Vivisection Hospital and one of its first physicians.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He was a trustee of the hospital with Lord Coleridge, Lord Hatherton, Rev.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He treated over 100 patients a week at the hospital without fee or reward.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] In 1912, he became the first permanent chairman of the London and Provincial Anti-Vivisection Society Committee.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He was also president of the Oxford Branch.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Wall was a member of the British Medical Association.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Sidney Trist described Wall as "the gentlest of critics, most generous in his commendation, absolutely unselfish, of unchallengeable loyalty and full of the spirit of forgiveness".
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] A memorial headstone was planned by Wall's friends in tribute of a "notable champion for the just and merciful treatment of animals".
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Ada Cole was born on Croxton Hall Farm near Thetford on the Norfolk/Suffolk border.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She was a daughter of Louisa Henrietta (née Clarke) and Edward Cole, an eloped couple, and was one of ten children, of whom only five survived infancy.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She was educated at home by her mother and a relative, Mrs.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] The family were tenant-farmers of some eleven hundred acres and used Shire horses and oxen to work the land.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] The children thus grew up surrounded by horses and cattle, and had dogs and a donkey.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Louisa Cole died unexpectedly in 1883, aged fifty-two.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] It was discovered that Edward Cole had been living a double life with Emily Clarke, whom he married in 1888, having already had two children with her.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Ada and her younger sister Effie left home for London soon after their mother's death.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] From 1883, Cole worked as a nurse at the thirty-year-old London Fever Hospital near King's Cross.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] At that time, before the era of motorized transport, horses were the major means of transport and haulage.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] The suffering of cab horses had already prompted Anna Sewell's famous tale, *Black Beauty*, first published in 1877 by Jarrolds of Norwich.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Cole was just as dismayed as that author at seeing overworked cab horses collapsing in the street from exhaustion and ill health.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Having been raised around animals, she knew they should be handled with compassion and respect.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Stray cats and dogs were at the time also often hunted and kept in laboratories for operations without anesthetic.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Cole became an early anti-vivisectionist and a vegetarian.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1886, both sisters became Roman Catholics, Ada taking the name of St Francis of Assisi as her baptismal name.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] After her sister became a nun, Cole took on private nursing work in the 1890s in the UK and in Europe.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] When she began to suffer from poor health, she moved to Norwich in 1890 where she worked as a district nurse until 1911 in the St Georges area, a poor district where she set up a club for impecunious Catholic girls.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] While in Norwich, Cole would visit the Cattle Market where she reprimanded the cattle handlers if she saw them handling the animals with brutality.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1906, Cole published, with Scientific Press, a booklet on nursing, called *Lectures on home nursing for the poor*.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] The booklet is now available as a classic reprint.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1910, Cole's health deteriorated and she was diagnosed with pulmonary tuberculosis.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She gave up nursing temporarily and moved to Cley-next-the-Sea, on the North Norfolk Coast, in order to rest and get well.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1911, somewhat recovered, Cole went to visit her younger sister, now the mother of a convent in Antwerp.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] One day, while passing the docks with her sister, Cole saw lines of horses who, ill and exhausted at the end of their working lives, had been sent from Britain to be disposed of in overseas abattoirs.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She was appalled at their brutal treatment.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She did not object to the eating of horses or their slaughter for meat per se but wanted more humane conditions for their transport to slaughterhouses.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] The invention of the internal combustion engine meant that many working horses had become redundant.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] By 1906, nearly 50,000 worn-out horses per year were being exported on British ships to the continent for meat or vivisection without anesthetic.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Cole researched the situation, working with the RSPCA and the Brussels Society for the Protection of Animals, watching and recording the journeys of horses and mules, often without access to food or water.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Once back home again in Cley, she corresponded with relevant authorities and kept detailed records on, for example, the number of animals arriving in Antwerp each year, the number sent to veterinary colleges for vivisection and those slaughtered in abattoirs in Antwerp.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She contributed to newspapers, gave public talks and was joined by others in sympathy with her actions and ideals.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] These included Stephen Coleridge, John Galsworthy and Alfred Munnings.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1914, largely as a result of her efforts, the first Exportation of Horses Act was passed in Britain.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] It only limited export to five ports and only prevented horses in very poor health from being exported.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Owing to the outbreak of war, it was never really put into effect.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] When the first world war broke out in 1914, Cole joined her sister Effie in Belgium.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She worked as a Red Cross nurse treating German and allied soldiers.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She also helped allied soldiers to escape back to their homes via underground networks that included her sister's convent.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Cole also distributed resistance newspapers.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She was arrested on August 3, 1918, and held in the Antwerp Military Prison which was also known, jokingly, as the Patriots' Hotel.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Interrogated and at times in solitary confinement, she then stood trial on November 1, 1918, and was sentenced to a year in prison in Germany.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Saved by the Armistice, she was freed on November 11.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She had kept a diary throughout the war, hiding the texts under the floorboards at the convent.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Three articles in the Eastern Daily Press October 1919 were derived from them.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1920, she received, along with her sister who had also been imprisoned, the Decoration Civique or Civic Decoration, a reward for exceptional acts of bravery, devotion or humanity.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] It was granted to her by Albert king of Belgium for her bravery, self-sacrifice and humanitarian actions during the war.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Although temporarily halted during the wartime hostilities, the transport of unfit horses to the continent for butchery continued after the war, as horse dealers eager for profit found loopholes in the 1914 act.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Efforts were made to encourage trade abroad in dead meat instead of live, but freshly killed meat was more popular on the continent.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Cole continued to work with help from, for example, the RSPCA, the Belgian SPCA, and Lord Mark Lambourne, to pressure the Minister of Agriculture to improve inspections and slaughter conditions in France and Belgium.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Newspaper articles, posters around London and a meeting at the Royal Albert Hall in May 1921, at which Cole spoke, all helped to sway public opinion so that a tax of £20 was levied on every horse, mule or ass exported live from Britain, thus making the trade uneconomic for horse dealers.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In the 1920s, Cole spoke publicly all over the country, gathering high-profile supporters such as John Buchan, who later became Governor General of Canada, and the Swedish anti-vivisectionist Emily Lind-af-Hageby and the Duchess of Hamilton.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Her aim was to stop the export of horses completely as it was hard to verify that the slaughter techniques in continental abattoirs were humane.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1928, Cole founded the International League for the Protection of Horses.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1929, she established Klondyke Horse Abattoir at Bourne, Lincolnshire, an abattoir designed to slaughter horses humanely.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1925, Cole and Jules Ruhl produced a controversial film for the RSPCA depicting the inhumane slaughter of export horses in Belgium that featured graphic footage taken at the village of Terhagon in 1914.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] The Departmental Committee of the Ministry of Agriculture alleged that the film featured staged slaughter footage by paid butchers.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Cole and Lady Simon planned a campaign to counteract the statements by the Departmental Committee.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] However, it was decided by the RSPCA that "it would not be expedient to conduct such a campaign".
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In July 1925, she was dismissed from the RSPCA for conducting a campaign outside of the Society.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] She campaigned against the exportation of worn-out horses; work which was not sanctioned by the RSPCA Council.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Cole commented that "I could have resigned but I preferred to allow them to dismiss me... the attitude of the R.S.P.C.A. with regard to the traffic in old horses has always been unsatisfactory".
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In response she formed the Old Horse Traffic Committee with Lady Simon as chairman.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Cole intended to get reinstated in the RSPCA as an organizer for the prevention of traffic in old horses.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Fairholme, chief secretary of the RPSCA requested for a requisition with at least 150 secured signatures to summon an "extraordinary general meeting".
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Cole sent requisition papers, signed by over 250 RSPCA members to their headquarters in February 1927.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] A controversial RSPCA meeting presided by Sir William Gentle was held in June 1927.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] There was divided opinion about Cole organizing a new special department of the Society to end the practice of exporting horses to Europe for slaughter.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] There were 173 votes in favour of the resolution and 100 against.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Cole's Old Horse Traffic Committee became the International League Against the Export of Horses for Butchery in 1928.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1930, Cole moved its offices to Bloomsbury Square.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] The organization amalgamated with the National Council to Prevent the Export of Horses for Butchery in 1935 and was renamed the International League for Horses.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1937, it became the International League for the Protection of Horses (ILPH).
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] The League's work has been credited for driving the Exportation of Horses Act which was passed in 1937.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Brigadier-General Sir George Cockerill was honorary director of ILPH in 1939.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] The ILPH was re-branded as World Horse Welfare in 2008.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Her remains were cremated at Golders Green Crematorium, among those president were Sir Robert Gower of the RSPCA and De Vere Summers.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] In 1932, the Ada Cole Memorial Stables, a home for old and ill-treated horses, were established in her memory.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Ledgers of the first residents show that some were military horses and mules brought back from fighting on the continent.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] The stables were merged with Redwings Horse Sanctuary in 2005.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] A book about Cole's life titled *She Heard Their Cry*, written by Joyce Rushen, was published in 1972 by ACMS Publishing.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Parallels have been drawn between Cole and another courageous Norfolk nurse, Edith Cavell, whose execution by Germans in 1915 made all aware of the danger of resistance work.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] Ada Cole Avenue in Snetterton was named after her.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-cole] From a sonnet entitled *A Friend in Need* on Ada Cole by Sir George Cockerill who became chair of the International League after Cole's death.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Ada Pike was born near Henley-on-Thames, South Oxfordshire, England.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Her parents emigrated to New Zealand with their four girls and one boy in 1873, arriving on the *Merope* in Lyttelton on 31 October of that year.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] She attended Avonside School from 1874, and Christchurch West High School in 1876, where she then worked as a pupil-teacher from 1877 to 1881.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Wells was awarded a scholarship to attend Canterbury College in 1881.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] In 1884, aged 20, she married Harry Wells, the cathedral organist and choirmaster.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Twelve years Ada's senior, with a violent temper and fondness for alcohol, he was a poor financial manager.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Ada's marital experience – where she was, at times, the family breadwinner – strengthened her belief that women should have economic independence.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Albans School which was situated in a poor working class part of Christchurch.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] With her husband's help, Ada put on concerts in aid of the school prize fund.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] In 1892, Ada, pregnant, sought two months' leave of absence.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] The North Canterbury Education Board was inclined to grant this.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] However, Ada was opposed by the headmaster, James Speight, who wrote a long letter on 'the delinquencies of Mrs.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Rather than being granted leave of absence, Ada was dismissed.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] In the 1880s, working within the Women's Christian Temperance Union New Zealand (WCTU NZ), Ada was active in the women's suffrage movement.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] While Kate Sheppard was the public face of the WCTU NZ's campaign for the enfranchisement of women, Ada was an organiser.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] In 1893 New Zealand became the first self-governing country in the world in which all women had the right to vote in parliamentary elections.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] In 1892, Ada established the Canterbury Women's Institute with Professor Alexander Bickerton, an organisation similar to the Women's Franchise Leagues in other parts of the country; for many years, she was president.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] In 1896 when the National Council of Women of New Zealand was formed, she became its first secretary.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] From 1899 to 1906, Ada was an elected member of the Ashburton and North Canterbury United Charitable Aid Board.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] She was associated with the Prison Gate Mission for the rehabilitation of ex-prisoners.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] A founding member of the National Council of Women in 1896, she was the first secretary.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] In 1905 Wells inherited the family house in Merivale, Christchurch after her mother died.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] From this address she continued practicing massage therapy, also her mother's profession, studied Anthroposophy, and continued her activism.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Ada died in Christchurch on 22 March 1933 and was buried at the Waimairi Cemetery.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] The Ministry for Culture and Heritage now offers an Ada Wells Memorial Prize for Undergraduate Students.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] As a member of the National Peace Council, Ada spoke out strongly against conscription and war, and helped support conscientious objectors during the First World War.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Wells advocated a meatless diet and was a vegetarianism activist.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] At the 1897 conference of the National Council of Women, Wells promoted an ovo-lacto vegetarian diet.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] She authored magazine articles supportive of naturopathy and vegetarianism.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Wells was an anti-vaccinationist and opposed vivisection.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] In 1898, Ada and Margaret Sievwright advocated for the economic independence of women, a continuing theme throughout her life.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] She also advocated for the repeal of the Contagious Diseases Act (1869), which legislated for the compulsory inspection of women and detention on suspicion of carrying venereal disease.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] The act was eventually repealed in 1910.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] She campaigned for the corollary to women's suffrage, women's right to stand for Parliament.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] This was ultimately granted in 1919, though no woman was elected until 1933, when Elizabeth McCoombs was voted in to the New Zealand Parliament.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] A member of the Labour Party, Ada was, between 1917 and 1919, the first woman member of the Christchurch City Council.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] In keeping with her educational background, Ada was the City Council representative on the Board of Governors of Christchurch Technical College, where she was the sole woman member.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Wells is represented in a fictional account of her life and those of her daughter, Bim, and fellow suffragist, Kate Sheppard.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] The book, *Farewell Speech* (1990) is written by Wells's great granddaughter, Rachel McAlpine.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] The book was later adapted into an award-winning play by Cathy Downes in 1993.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/ada-wells] Wells and her marriage to Harry feature in a 2015 musical, That Bloody Woman, written by Luke Di Somma and Gregory Cooper about the suffragist movement in New Zealand.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] He began an apprenticeship as a bookseller, but fell ill and turned in the self-study on various natural remedies, through which he became a lay practitioner.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] For a philosophy of medicine he most strongly advocated a "Return to Nature", utilizing natural food, clean water, fresh air, earthen clay, as well as time spent in nature itself.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] Eckertal in 1895 he founded the Naturopathic Institute Jungborn.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] The most prominent patient was Franz Kafka.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] In 1918 Just founded the healing clay Society in Blankenburg (Harz), and started the company, Luvos.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] His main work attracted interest in India and led there to set up a still existing natural medicine hospital in Pune.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] Just held a Christianized religious ideology based on the idea that salvation could be regained by understanding how primordial man used to live.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] He held the belief that in the beginning, "all creatures, frog and mouse, hedgehog and hare, deer, and elk, fox and badger" all lived in harmony with the Creator.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] Animals remained in their pristine state of grace, whilst man fell.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] He believed that by studying the behaviour of animals, people could experience salvation of the soul.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] Just believed that Jesus came to redeem humanity by teaching how to live in harmony with nature.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] His best known work *Kehrt zur Natur zurück!* (*Back to Nature!*), was translated by Benedict Lust in 1903.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] Just opposed everything that was not in accordance with nature.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] He opposed automobiles, modern housing and chemical agriculture.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] He rejected medical science and criticized vaccination and vivisection.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] He believed that vaccines were poisons that inflict misery upon people.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] Just advocated morning fasts and a raw food vegetarian diet of unprocessed foods.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] He considered a diet of fruit and nuts to be the best natural foods for man.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/adolf-just] He rejected the use of any drugs but was also critical of homeopathy and gymnastics which he considered artificial.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The **Animal Defence and Anti-Vivisection Society** (**ADAVS**), also known as the **Animal Defence Society** was an animal welfare organisation, co-founded in England, in 1906, by Lizzy Lind af Hageby, and Nina Douglas-Hamilton, Duchess of Hamilton.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The objective of the Society was a "Consistent Opposition to all forms of Cruelty to Animals and Abolition of Vivisection".
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society was known for its support of humane slaughter.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society's assets were transferred to a charity, The Animal Defence Trust that was registered in 1971.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] It was based for many years at Animal Defence House, 15 St James's Place, London, and ran a 237-acre animal sanctuary at Ferne House near Shaftesbury, Dorset, an estate owned by the Duke and Duchess of Hamilton.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] An early member of the Society's executive council was Alice Drakoules who was a lifelong campaigner for animal welfare and a keen supporter of the Society.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] She helped the Society campaign for humane slaughter, licensed slaughterhouses and for an end to performing animals.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society came to widespread attention during the Brown Dog affair (1903–1910), which began when Lind af Hageby infiltrated the vivisection in University College London of a brown terrier dog.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The subsequent description of the experiment in her book, *The Shambles of Science* (1903) – in which she wrote that the dog had been conscious throughout and in pain – led to a protracted scandal and a libel case, which the accused researcher won.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The affair continued for several years, making a name both for Lind af Hageby and for the Society.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society was associated with Hageby's International Humanitarian Bureau.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] It published *The Anti-Vivisection and Humanitarian Review* in 1929 and *Progress Today: The Humanitarian and Anti-Vivisection Review* in the 1930s.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1933, members of the Society's executive council included Sara Blomfield, Charlotte Despard, Douglas S.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1959, the Society protested against a mass pigeon shoot throughout the East of England the Midlands.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] Despite supporting total abolition of vivisection the Society advocated reform of animal slaughter.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society called for legislation making humane slaughter compulsory.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society advertised its own "humane killer" for sale, a type of captive bolt pistol.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1923, the Society advocated a statement of minimum slaughter reform that was sent to the Cabinet Committee.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] Their proposal was that local authorities should be under obligation to approve only types of human killers for use in the slaughterhouse within their districts and that inspectors should be allowed to enter the slaughterhouse to enforce the Act.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] They urged that all slaughtermen should be licensed and that any other method of killing animals for food should be prohibited.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society opposed the use of the knife and poleaxe in slaughter.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] Lizzy Lind af Hageby and Duchess Nina Douglas-Hamilton both visited slaughterhouses and tested the "humane killer" and criticized the cruelty of the poleaxe.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1924, a report they signed had found that a pig had to be hit four times on the head before it was rendered unconscious and that the humane killer rendered twenty animals unconscious by the first shot.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1925, it was reported that the Duchess of Hamilton had witnessed 52 animals being slaughtered in a single afternoon in pursuance of the statutory use of the humane killer.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society supported the Slaughter of Animals Act 1933.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The humane killer gained support from slaughterhouse workers.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] John Dodds, superintendent of the Carlisle abattoir became an expert adviser to the Society in their campaign for compulsory use of the humane killer.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society's Slaughter Reform Department consisted of John Dodds and Constance Warner.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1937, the Society organized an exhibition in London with demonstrations of humane killers.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1939, the Society angered the poultry industry by campaigning against the use of battery cage hens.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society stated that the hens are imprisoned in the battery system in a confined space with no contact with fresh air and grass.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society campaigned for the abolition of private slaughterhouses and the creation of humanely-conducted public abattoirs.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] In 1929, the Society opened the "Model Humane Abattoir" in Letchworth.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The building was owned by the Society and was used to demonstrate humane slaughter and hygienic treatment of meat.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The humane model abattoir was built on a site covering two acres and planned to deal with 20,000 animals a year.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The site contained a slaughter hall, lairs, cooling hall for cattle, general loading stage, chill rooms, engine room, a large lecture theatre and a veterinary inspection area.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society also planned to build a bacon factory in which pigs were shot with the humane killer.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The model humane abattoir gained support from the National Council for Animals' Welfare.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Society stated that meat from the abattoir was to be sold by their own company.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] Duchess Nina Douglas-Hamilton was a vegetarian in her personal life but in 1928 became the head of a humane butcher's shop.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] Following Lind af Hageby's death in December 1963, the Society's assets were transferred to a trust, The Animal Defence Trust, which continues to offer grants for animal-protection projects.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] The Animal Defence Trust registered as a charity in 1971.
[src:animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society/animal-defence-and-anti-vivisection-society] NC State University Libraries holds a large collection of pamphlets from the Animal Defence and Anti-Vivisection Society.
